The spring is located at the eastern foot of {{ill|Mount Kujū|ja|九重山|12=draft|12=draft}}, on the slopes of {{ill|Mount Kurodake (Ōita)|ja|黒岳 (大分県)|12=draft|12=draft}} (elevation 1,586&nbsp;m).<ref name="visit-oita" /> It also serves as an entrance to hiking trails leading up Mount Kurodake.<ref>{{Cite web|和書 |url=https://www.city.taketa.oita.jp/sightseeing/nature/pdf/tozanzu.pdf |title=Kuju Mountain Range Hiking Map |publisher=Taketa City |format=PDF |accessdate=2019-05-25 }}</ref>
{{Citation needed|The name "Hakusui" (白水, meaning "white water") is derived from the fact that the high carbon dioxide content causes surrounding rocks and soil to turn white, giving the flowing water a whitish appearance.|date=May 2019}}
The mineral water, also known as "Ramune Water," is drinkable and takes on a taste similar to cider when mixed with sugar.<ref name="park" /> Drinking the water at the source is free of charge. Visitors can take home one 500ml PET bottle per person for free.<ref name="visit-oita" /><ref>{{Cite web|和書 |url=http://www.i-oita.net/spot/hot_springs/yufu/9756.html |title=Hakusui Mineral Springs |work=i-Navi Ōita |publisher=[[Ōita Broadcasting System]] |accessdate=2019-05-25 }}</ref>
To the west of Hakusui Mineral Springs is the {{ill|Oike Spring Group|ja|男池湧水群|12=draft|12=draft}}, which has been designated as one of {{ill|Japan’s 100 Famous Waters|ja|名水百選|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name="park" />
On October 4, 2019, the area surrounding Hakusui Mineral Springs, including the drinking springs in the Asono district of Shōnai Town, was added to the {{ill|Yufuin Onsen Village|ja|湯布院温泉郷|12=draft|12=draft}} as part of an expansion of the {{ill|National Health Resort|ja|国民保養温泉地|12=draft|12=draft}} designation. Previously, only {{ill|Yufuin Onsen|ja|由布院温泉|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Yunohira Onsen|ja|湯平温泉|12=draft|12=draft}} were included under the "Yufuin Onsen" designation.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.oita-press.co.jp/1010000000/2019/09/07/JD0058455851 |title=Yufu City as a Whole Designated as "Yufuin Onsen Village" |newspaper=Ōita Gōdō Shimbun |date=2019-09-07 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|和書 |url=http://www.city.yufu.oita.jp/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/hoyouonsentikeikakusho.pdf |title=Yufuin Onsen Village (Yufuin Onsen, Yunohira Onsen, Tsukahara Onsen, Shōnai Onsen, Hasama Onsen) National Health Resort Plan |publisher=Yufu City |date=2019-10-04 |format=PDF |accessdate=2019-10-10 }}</ref>
